## Data, Data, Everywhere

We live in a day and age where data is being generated at a pace that is faster than ever! Much of this data is also unstructured, untidy, and now also dominated by text format. Lately, I have been exploring the utility of the tidytext package to process such messy natural language data and draw insights.

In this short example, we will grab the Twitter data using the rtweet package, process it using tidytext and tidyverse, and visualize it using ggplot and leaflet.

## üîç Searching for Tweets

First, let us load all the packages we will need. We will use the rtweet package to query the tweets, tidytext, and tidyverse to clean and mine the text data, and ggplot and leaflet for visualization. rtweet is an R client for accessing Twitter‚Äôs REST and stream APIs.

``` r
library(rtweet)
library(tidytext)
library(tidyverse)
library(leaflet)
library(ggthemes)
```

As an example, let‚Äôs scrape tweets that use the hashtag ‚Äò\#omicron‚Äô in them. We can do this using the `search_tweet()` function from the rtweet package.

``` r
tweets <- search_tweets(q = "#omicron", n = 18000,
                                      lang = "en",
                                      include_rts = FALSE)
```

## üßπ Cleaning the data

Let‚Äôs peek into the raw tweet data

``` r
tail(tweets$text)
```

At the first glance, it is clear that there‚Äôs quite a bit of data cleaning required. For example, you may want to remove URLs from scraped tweets. You may even want to get rid of emoticons, punctuation, etc. while at it. As an example, let us remove the URLs from the tweets and look at the data.

``` r
tweets<- tweets %>%
  mutate(stripped_text = gsub("http.*","",text))

tail(tweets$stripped_text)
```

    ## [1] ""                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             
    ## [2] "NIOSH N95 masks and protect yourself wherever possible from any long-term #COVID19 effects. #Omicron looks to peak in rolling geo areas over the next weeks and enter an endemic phase. Vaccines are a map for your immune system to later follow preventing pockets of real infections."     
    ## [3] "#Omicron: #Maharashtra Govt to impose night curfew (11pm-5am) from Jan 10, bar movement of people in groups of 5 or more\n\nSwimming pools, gyms, spas, beauty  salons, zoos, museums, &amp; entertainment parks to remain closed\n\nHair cutting salons and malls to operate at 50% capacity"
    ## [4] "My daughter is glad her school remains open: ‚Äúthe state does not recommend ‚Äúany automatic trigger or threshold‚Äù used to suspend in-person learning.‚Äù <U+2066>@DonnaStGeorge<U+2069> #Omicron  "                                                                                               
    ## [5] "From January 10, #Maharashtra government announces new restrictions in order to contain the #Omicron variant. According to the restrictions, no movement in groups of 5 or more people will be allowed from 5 am to 11 pm. No movement from 11 pm to 5 am except for essential purposes."     
    ## [6] "As Omicron cases increase, Ontario returns to a modified Step 2 of the COVID-19 roadmap. Here are the updates to help you out.\n\n"

Now that the URLs are gone, the text starts to look a bit cleaner. However, you might not want to do all the cleaning manually. Thankfully, the tidytext package comes with the unnest\_tokens() function that will magically clean up all the text. It will convert the text to lowercase, get rid of punctuation marks, and add the unique tweet id for each occurrence of the unique word. Let‚Äôs use it over our URL-stripped text data.

``` r
tweets_clean <- tweets %>%
  dplyr::select(stripped_text) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, stripped_text)
```

## üó£ What is the chatter about?

Let us grab and plot the 25 most frequent words from our data.

``` r
tweets_clean %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(25) %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = word, y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  xlab(NULL) +
  coord_flip() +
      labs(x = "",
      y = "Count",
      title = "Unique frequent words found in tweets")+ggthemes::theme_economist()
```

## üßπ More cleaning

Spot any issues? Looks like we need to clean up the data even more. We need to filter all the filler/‚Äòstop words‚Äô such as ‚Äúin,‚Äù ‚Äúand,‚Äù ‚Äúa,‚Äù ‚Äúof,‚Äù etc. Again, thanks to the inbuilt stop\_words data included with the tidytext pacakge, we can remove all the filler words from the text. Let‚Äôs test it out with our data.

Before filtering out the stop words our tweets\_clean data contains 494698 observations.

``` r
tweets_clean <- tweets_clean %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word")
```

After filtering out stop words our data has 288447 observations. Let us now recreate our previous plot with these clean data.

``` r
tweets_clean %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(25) %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = word, y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  xlab(NULL) +
  coord_flip() +
      labs(x = "",
      y = "Count",
      title = "Unique frequent words found in tweets")+ggthemes::theme_economist()
```

## üó∫ Mapping the tweets

Let us find out where these tweets come from. For that, we first need to add the latitude and longitude information for each tweet. This can be done using the `lat_lng()` function from the rtweet package.

``` r
tweets_with_latlons <- rtweet::lat_lng(tweets)
```

``` r
tweets_with_latlons %>%
  count(place_full_name, sort = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(location = reorder(place_full_name,n)) %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  top_n(20) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = location,y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "Count",
       title = "Omicron Tweets - top 20 unique locations ")+ggthemes::theme_economist()
```

<img src="{{< blogdown/postref >}}index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png" width="672" />

Let us create a spatial map of these tweets.

``` r
leaflet::leaflet() %>%
  leaflet::addProviderTiles("OpenStreetMap.Mapnik") %>%
  leaflet::addCircles(data = tweets_with_latlons, 
             color = "blue")
```
